We then determined whether the formation of DnaJ-a3’ complexes requires DnaK. The most direct experiment to show this is to identify DnaJ-&C-his associations in AdnaK52 mutants that lack DnaK. However, this experiment was unsuccessful because AdnaK5P mutants have very low levels of DnaJ (Sell et al., 1990) and the expression of rY2-C-his proteins causes severe cellular defects in AdnaK52 mutants even in the uninduced state (unpublished data), which is in agreement with earlier reports on AdnaK52 mutants (Bukau and Walker, 1990). As an alternative approach, we examined whether untagged 03* associates with histidine-tagged DnaJ in AdnaK52 mu-

tants. The dnaJ gene was cloned into pUHE212-1 such that this plasmid expresses recombinant DnaJ with six additional histidine residues at the N-terminus (DnaJ-Nhis). DnaJ-N-his is biologically active, as revealed by in vivo complementation of the temperature sensitivity and h resistance of AdnaJ47 mutants. AdnaK52 mutants (BB1553) carrying pUHE212-l(dnaJ) and pDMI,l plasmids were induced with IPTG, and extracts of these cells were subjected to IMAC. lmmunoblots of the imidazole elution fractions revealed that DnaJ-N-his was efficiently bound to the Ni*+column and eluted at 40-l 20 mM imidazole with an elution peak at 70 mM (Figure 7A; fraction 15). A significant fraction of rY2 was specifically bound to the column and exhibited exactly the same imidazole elution characteristics as DnaJ-N-his (Figure 78). We then expressed DnaJ-N-his in dnaK+ cells and analyzed the copurification of 032with DnaJ-N-his (Figures 8A and 88). The elution profiles of the two proteins were quantitatively and qualitatively identical to those found for AdnaK52 mutants, indicating that the association of @ with DnaJ-N-his is as efficient in AdnaK52 mutants as in dnaK+ cells. Taken together, these experiments provide evidence that under our conditions, the formation of DnaJ-N-his&* complexes occurs independently of DnaK, and the formation of DnaK-@-C-his complexesoccurs independently of DnaJ.
Discussion
This report presents evidence for the direct physical association of the HSPs DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE with 03*, the heat shock-specific transcription factor of E. coli. We demonstrate the specific copurification of these HSPs with I+*. The purification strategy relied on the tagging of both 03* and DnaJ with histidines that allowed isolation of 03*-HSP complexes from crude E. coli lysates using IMAC. Since the histidine tagging did not affect the in vivo functions of either protein, this method may prove useful in complementing existing methods for studying protein-protein interactions.
When E. coli lysates containing rY2 tagged with a histidine hexamer were subjected to IMAC, three HSPs, DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE, were retained with 03’on a Ni2+column. Moreover, IMAC of lysates containing authentic 032 and

