Associationof @ with DnaK,GrpE, and DnaJ 839

histidine-tagged DnaJ revealed the retention of oZ together with DnaJ on a Ni2+column. These findings provide strong evidence for the physical association of 032 with DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE in vivo. Together, our results allow us to exclude several potential experimental artifacts. Firstly, the tagging of a3* and DnaJ with histidines did not affect the properties of these proteins in vivo. Furthermore, for histidine-tagged oX purified by Ni2’-affinity chromatography, we have proved that it is active in in vitro transcription (unpublished data); thus, the histidine tag appears to interfere neither with the interaction between the @ subunit and core RNA polymerase nor with the recognition of the heat shock promoter sequence by the tagged o factor. Together, this is strong evidence that the integrity of the structure and function of both proteins is maintained. Secondly, formation of a32-DnaJ complexes occurred regardless of whether the histidine tag is fused to the 032 or the DnaJ moiety. This unequivocally excludes that the interaction of DnaJ with 032 is mediated via the histidine tag of the @ protein.
Thirdly, formation of 03*-DnaK complexes occurred regardless of whether 032was tagged at the N-or C-terminus. This largely excludes two formally possible artifacts. The first artifact is, should DnaK bind to the hexamer histidine moiety itself, it would be expected to affect the high affinity binding of 03* to the Ni2+ chelating column. This is not observed, independently of whether the histidine tags are located at the N- or C-terminus of 03’. The second artifact is, should DnaK bind to conformational distortions of 032 induced by the terminal runs of histidines, one would have to predict a comparable effect of this moiety in both the N-and C-terminal portions of the molecule. This, however, appears highly unlikely. Fourthly, the following lines of evidence exclude the possibility that the o~~-HSP complexes are protein aggregates that result from misfolding of 03* due to its overproduction. First, the cells that were used for our experiments were only partially induced by IPTG (50 PM IPTG for lo-60 min) and therefore contain only intermediate levels of tagged 032. These levels of tagged 03* did not affect continuous growth of the cells (data not shown). Second, DnaJ-03* complexes were present in cells that contained wild-type levels of untagged @ and histidine-tagged DnaJ. Third, under the inducing conditions used, tagged a32 did not self-aggregate but rather existed as a monomeric species as long as DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE were absent (see Figure 5C). Taken together, the demonstration of the physical association of o32with DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE is strong support for genetic data indicating roles for these three HSPs in heat shock gene regulation in E. coli (see Introduction). Since Hsp70 proteins also appear to be involved in heat shock gene regulation in eukaryotes (Craig and Jacobsen, 1964), direct interactions between Hsp70 and heat shock transcription factors may play a role in these cells as well.
While the association of a32with DnaK may have been expected from genetic data, that of ap with DnaJ is surprising. It is quite interesting that both associations occur independently and have distinctly different biochemical properties. This conclusion is based on the findings that a3*-DnaJ complexes existed in extracts of AdftaK52 mu-

tants, and 032-DnaK (and possibly GrpE) complexes existed in extracts of dnaJ47(am) mutants; that @-DnaW GrpE complexes were disrupted by ATP, whereas I+*DnaJ complexes persisted in the presence of ATP as well as after ATP elution of DnaK and GrpE; and that c+DnaJ complexes were more stable in the presence of imidazole than the complexes between 032 and DnaK/GrpE. The quantity of c+DnaJ and 032-DnaWGrpE complexes was not dramatically altered in extracts of AdnaK52 mutants or dnaJ47(am) mutants as compared with extracts of wildtype cells. However, our experimental approach has limitations in the detection of less obvious quantitative differences in complex formation, and therefore we cannot rule out a possible cooperativity between DnaK and DnaJ in complex formation. Furthermore, our data provide no information on the relative affinities of DnaJ and DnaK for 03*. For instance, it cannot be excluded that in wild-type cells that contain only lo-30 molecules per cell of 032,the number of 032-DnaK complexes is considerably smaller than the number of aA2-DnaJ complexes, even though DnaK (approximately 5000 molecules per cell) is in a large excess over DnaJ (less than 200 molecules per cell) (Neidhardt and Van Bogelen, 1967). The ATP-dependent release of r~~ from DnaK is a property that is common to all known substrates of Hsp70 chaperones, and thus our data indicate that 032is bound to DnaK as a substrate. The concomitant ATP-mediated release of GrpE suggests that GrpE is associated with DnaK-03* complexes. The known ability of GrpE to interact physically with DnaK (Johnson et al., 1989) and to stimulate its ATPase activity (Liberek et al., 1991a)is likelytoaccountfor itscoelution with DnaK. The lower abundance of GrpE as compared with DnaK in these complexes (as well as in total cell extracts) is consistent with a catalytic role of GrpE. The instability of 03*-DnaK/GrpE complexes in the presence of imidazole is revealed by the shift of the DnaWGrpE elution peaks by approximately eight fractions to lower imidazole concentrations as compared with the elution peaks of o32 and DnaJ. lmidazole groups readily react with electrophilic groups, and this may disrupt ionic protein-protein interactions, especially if acidic proteins such as DnaK and GrpE are involved. In addition, imidazole has hydrophobic properties that may also account for the destabilization of a32-DnaK/GrpE complexes.
While our data clearly demonstrate specific 032-DnaW GrpE and 03*-DnaJ complexes, they do not exclude the existence of additional complexes that involve 032and all three proteins, DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE. For instance, the possibility exists that a3*-DnaWGrpE complexes also contain DnaJ which, after ATP elution of DnaK and GrpE, either remains bound to o32or elutes and rebinds to other, monomeric cr3*molecules that are complexed to the column. Moreover, the stoichiometric relationships of the individual components of each complex have yet to be determined.
The demonstration that two HSPs independently bind to C? has major implications concerning the principles that govern the signal transduction pathway of the heat shock regulon. Our data are consistent with two alternative scenarios that may account for the roles of DnaK, DnaJ, and

Cell 840

GrpE in heat shock gene regulation at 30°C. According to one scenario, the first step is the binding of DnaJ to @, which then targets DnaK and GrpE to bind to 032. The subsequent association of all three proteins, DnaJ, DnaK, and GrpE, renders 03’biologically inactive and susceptible to degradation. To account for the stoichiometric differences of the DnaK and DnaJ bound to oZ2, it has to be postulated that the 03*-HSP complexes either are very large and contain a large molar excess of DnaK, or DnaJ has a catalytic function and readily dissociates upon binding of DnaK to the 03*-DnaJ complex. In addition to the DnaJ-mediated binding of DnaK to 03*, a DnaJindependent binding of DnaK to c?* exists that might be nonspecific and eventually nonfunctional. A quite similar situation has been described for the binding of DnaJ and DnaK to the nucleoprotein complex that is formed at the origin of replication of bacteriophage h during the initiation of DNA replication (Alfano and McMacken, 1989). According to a second scenario, DnaJ and DnaK compete for binding to cr3’and form independent 03’-DnaJ and 03’DnaK/GrpE complexes. However, the biological consequences of such competition are unclear, especially since genetic data indicate that DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE coordinately affect stability and activity of c? at 30% (Straus et al., 1989, 1990; Tilly et al., 1989). For either proposed scenario, it remains unclear whether it is free a3’or RNA polymerase-bound a3* that is the substrate for binding to DnaJ and DnaK.
The mechanism for the transduction of temperature effects into the signal pathway of the heat shock regulon remains to be determined. It is tempting to speculate that the cellular thermometer that receives intracellular stress signals is not primarily DnaK, but rather the coordinate activity of DnaJ and DnaK. One of several possible signal pathways is that upon stress induction both DnaJ and DnaK get increasingly bound to damaged proteins and thus become less available for binding to 032(Craig and Gross, 1991). This could account for the transient stabilization of 03* during the heat shock response. An alternative signal pathway is that temperature differentially affects the availability of DnaJ and DnaK for binding to 03*. Upon heat shock, DnaK might become bound to damaged proteins and thereby be less available for associating with 03*,while DnaJ might retain its availability for binding to 032.Association of 03* with DnaJ in the absence of DnaK after heat shock, as opposed to the presence of DnaK at 30°C, may in fact increase the stability of 032by preventing its degradation. However, the only evidence suggesting divergent regulatory roles of DnaJ at different temperatures is the puzzling finding that dnaJ missense mutations increase stability of d32at 30°C but not after heat shock (Straus et al., 1990). An additional consequence of this signal pathway is that during stress induction, DnaJ might become unavailable for the more unspecific chaperone functions of DnaK because it is bound to d3*. This transient lack of DnaJ function might temporarily freeze DnaK in a substrate-bound form with an ATPase activity that is lower than in the presence of DnaJ. Retardation of the release of DnaK-bound substrates might be biologically significant, since recent results indicate that chaperone-mediated re-

folding of some denatured proteins not only requires DnaK, DnaJ, and GrpE, but also GroEL and GroES (Martin et al., 1991; F.-U. Hart1 and T. Langer, personal communication). These proteins, however, appear limiting in the initial phase of heat stress and must be newly synthesized. In a more general context, DnaJ-directed specific chaperone functions of DnaK, such as the regulation of 032,might be quick, while nonspecific chaperone functions of DnaK might be slow.
Our finding that DnaJ associates with 032increases the number of substrates that are known to bind to DnaJ in the absence of DnaK. DnaJ stably associates with plasmid Pl-encoded RepA (Wickner, 1990) E. coli DnaB helicase (Liberek et al., 1990; Wold et al., 1982; Georgopoulos et al., 1990), and phage X-encoded P protein (Georgopoulos et al., 1990). In these cases, DnaJ appears to target DnaK to bind to the preformed DnaJ-substrate complexes. A reasonable speculation is that DnaJ provides specificity to the DnaK chaperone, which, by itself, has a broad, degenerative substrate specificity. However, in the case of @, it remains to be tested whether DnaJ indeed has such a targeting function for DnaK. In this context it will be interesting to examine the relationship between the members of the eukaryotic DnaJ and Hsp70 protein families
Experimental Procedures
Bacterial Strains and Plasmids Bacterial strains are listed in Table 1. Strain 682064 was constructed by Plvir transduction as follows. We mtroduced into strain GW4701 first a ma/PC+ allele by selection for Mal’ transductants, then a recA allele by selection for a linked Tc’ marker (zfi::TnlO) and screening for ultraviolet sensitivity. Strain 882296 carries an amber stop codon at nucleotide 202 of the coding sequence of dnaJ and therefore lacks DnaJ’ function. This mutant will be described in detail elsewhere. Plasmids pDMI,l (la@, Km’) (Lanzer. 1968) and pUHE21-2 (Ap’) (Bujard et al., 1987) have been described earlier. pUHE21 l-l (for construction of C-terminal histidinefusions)and pUHE212-1 (forconstruction of N-terminal histidine fusions) closely resemble the previously described pDS56 RBSII-6XHis plasmids (Ap’) (Stijber et al., 1990).
Media and Growth Conditions Bacteria were grown aerobically at 30% or at temperatures as indicated in 2 x YTor M9 minimal media (Miller, 1972) supplemented with glucose (0.4%) thiamine (0.001%) and appropriate amino acids (50 ug/ml). Antibiotics were used in the following concentrations: tetracycline (Tc), 10 hglml; kanamycin (Km), 40 hg/ml; ampicillin (Ap). 100 trg/ml.
Genetic Techniques and DNA Manipulations Pl vir transductions and transformations were done using standard techniques (Miller, 1972; Maniatis et al., 1989; Silhavy et al., 1984). Preparations of plasmid DNA and cloning of PCR-amplified fragments were carried out as described (Maniatis et al., 1989). The PCR amplification of the rpoH and dnaJ genes of strain MC4100 was done according to the instructions provided by the supplier of Taq polymerase (Perkin-Elmer Cetus). As primers, we used oligonucleotides (31-64 mers) that at their S’end were homologous to rpoHor dnaJsequences, and at their 5’ end carried recognition sites for restriction enzymes. Whenever required, appropriate translational signals were included. Plasmids pUHE21 I-l(rpoK)and pUHE21-2(rpoH). encoding o”C-his and untagged @, respectively, were constructed by cloning a PCRgenerated BamHI-EcoRI fragment carrying the rpoH+ gene into the EcoRl and BamHl sites of the vectors. Plasmid pUHE212-l(rpo/f). encoding @-N-his, was constructed by cloning a PCR-generated BamHI-Hindlll fragment carrying the rpoH’ gene into the Hindlll and BamHl sites of the vector. pUHE212-l(dnaS), encoding DnaJ-N-his.

