Complementation Assays Complementation tests for temperature-sensitive growth of rpoH765(am) mutants were carried out in 882073 cells transformed with pDMI,l and pUHE21 I-l(rpo/f), pUHE212-l(rpoH), or their parental plasmids. Cell viability at 43OC was determined by plating appropriate dilutions of 30°C-overnight cultures on LB agar plates containing O-500 nM IPTG, or by growing the cells in LB liquid media containing O-500 nfvf IPTG. Complementation of dnaJ47(am) mutants was done in 882296 cells transformed with pDMI,l and pUHE212-l(dnaJ). Cell viability at 43OC was determined as described for rpoH765(am) mutants. The ability to grow I. phages was determined at 30°C by hvir plating assays as described (Silhavy et al., 1984).
Pulse-Labeling Experiments Cell cultures were grown at 3O“C in M9 minimal medium to an OD, of 0.6, induced with IPTG (final concentration 50 PM), and, after addition of IPTG, immediately incubated at 43OC. At the indicated times, aliquots of 1 ml were labeled with 10 j&i of L-j?S]methionine (specific activity >800 Cilmmole, Amersham Corp.) for 2 min, followed by a chase for 5 min with unlabeled methionine (2 mM final concentration). The labeled cells were transferred to ice, washed in minimal medium and lysed by boiling in cracking buffer (see below). Aliquots of 10 nl were subjected to electrophoresis in 12.5% SDS-polyacrylamide gels. Gels were autoradiographed using Fuji RX films.
Purification of Histidine-Tagged Proteins Using MAC Cells producing histidine-tagged oZ and DnaJ were grown at 30°C in 1 liter of 2 x YTlAplKm medium to an OD, of I, At this point, IPTG (50 uM final concentration) was added, and after further growth of the culture for IO-60 min, the cells were collected by centrifugation (6,000 x g, 10 min, 4OC) and resuspended in 20 ml of cold lysis buffer A (50 mM Tris-HCI [pH 71,100 mM KCI, 1 mM EDTA, lysozyme). Thereafter, all manipulations weredoneat 4OC. Phenylmethylsulfonyl fluoridewas added to a final concentration of 1 mM, and soluble cell extracts were obtained by stirring the suspension for 30 min followed by sonification (5 x 10 s, level 7; Branson sonifier) and centrifugation (35,000 x g, 30 min). For IMAC, cell extracts were supplemented with MgCI, (1 mM, final concentration) and KCI (200 mM, final concentration) and loaded onto 4 ml NF+-nitrilotriacetic acid-agarose columns (prepared according to the manufacturers instructions [Diagen] and equilibrated with buffer A). Chromatography of the extracts was performed at 4OC using an FPLC system from Pharmacia LKB (flow rate of 0.5 mllmin). Loaded columns were first washed with 20 ml of buffer A, then developed by linear O-150 mM imidazole gradients (50 ml, in buffer A), followed by 1 M imidazole step gradients, and fractions of 1.5 ml were collected.
SDS-PAGE and Immunological Techniques Protein samples were mixed with equal volumes of 2 x cracking buffer (40 mM EDTA. 20% glycerol, 4% SDS, 10% j3-mercaptoethanol, 100 mM Tris-HCI [pH 6.81) boiled for 5 min and subjected to electrophoresis in 12.5% SDS-polyacrylamide gels as described (Laemmli, 1970). lmmunoblots were developed with alkaline phosphatase-conjugated anti-rabbit IgG as secondary antibodies (Promega), as described by Harlow and Lane (1988). Polyclonal antisera were raised against histidine-tagged DnaK, DnaJ, GrpE, and a32 that had been purified

under denaturing conditions by IMAC according to Hochuli et al. (1987, 1988). Dilutions for use in immunoblot experiments were as follows: @-C-his antiserum, l:lO,OOO; DnaK-N-his and DnaJ-N-his antisera, 1:7.000; GrpE-N-his antisera, 1:8.000.

Gel Filtration Protein samples were centrifuged (14,000 x g. 5 min). and aliquots of 200 pl were loaded onto a Pharmacia Superdex 75 column (flow rate 0.5 mllmin). As mobile phase, a buffer containing 50 mM Tris-HCI (pH 7) 200 mM KCI, 100 mM imidazole was used (flow rate 0.5 mllmin). Fractions of 300 pl were collected, and proteins were precipitated with trichloroacetic acid. The precipitate was prepared for SDS-PAGE. The molecular mass standards were apoferritin (440,000) bovine serum albumin (68,000), and carboanhydrase (29,000) (Sigma).

